{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480313"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:41:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:41:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"39"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/39"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.61,0.16,0.05,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"39"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112771"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/39"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"39"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94805"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6914"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7143"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14427"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15033"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41966"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48122"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112771"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a one-hour history of shortness of breath, sweating, and nausea. She has a medical history of Alzheimer\u0027s dementia, hypertension, hyperlipidaemia, and type 2 diabetes mellitus. Her regular medications include donepezil, amlodipine, atorvastatin, and metformin. She is an ex-smoker with a 30 pack year history. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears confused. Her pulse rate is 54/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is bilateral crepitation to the mid-zones of her lungs. Her jugular venous pressure is elevated to 5 cm above the sternal angle. An ECG is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following should NOT  be done during the management of this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oxygen therapy","Nitroglycerin","Intravenous fluids","Cardiac catheterisation","Intravenous dobutamine"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ECG shows ST elevation in the inferior leads (II, III, aVF) and lateral leads (V5, V6) with posterior extension (ST depression in V1-V3). This distribution is suggestive of an infero-posterio-lateral myocardial infarction. An important consideration in inferior-postero MI is the involvement of the right ventricle (RV). Signs suggesting acute right ventricular infarction include unexplained hypotension and bradycardia, as well as raised jugular venous pressure, all of which are present in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdministration of \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous fluids could be considered\u003C/strong\u003E. In right ventricular infarction, there is decreased preload, and fluid resuscitation helps to increase right ventricular filling and improve cardiac output. This is crucial before proceeding to definitive treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxygen therapy \u003C/strong\u003Eshould be initiated with an saturation target of 94% and above. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENitroglycerin\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in right ventricular infarction. It causes vasodilation which further decreases preload, worsening perfusion and potentially leading to profound hypotension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac catheterisation\u003C/strong\u003E for primary percutaneous coronary intervention is the definitive treatment for myocardial infarction and will need to be done.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous dobutamine\u003C/strong\u003E is an option for hemodynamic stabilisation if the patient has refractory hypotension despite adequate fluid administration whilst definitive therapy such as cardiac catheterisation is performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the initial management of right ventricular infarction focuses on improving right ventricular preload through fluid administration. This is followed by urgent cardiac catheterisation for definitive treatment of the underlying coronary artery occlusion, medications such as nitroglycerin should be avoided given the right ventricular infarction and hypotension.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Right ventricular involvement in inferior myocardial infarction can present with hypotension, bradycardia, and raised JVP.","Initial management of right ventricular infarction involves fluid resuscitation to increase right ventricular perfusion.","Nitrates and beta-blockers should be avoided in right ventricular infarction."],"references":["1. Inohara T, Kohsaka S, Fukuda K, Menon V. The challenges in the management of right ventricular infarction. European Heart Journal: Acute Cardiovascular Care. 2013;2(3):226-234. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24222834/","Warner MJ, Tivakaran VS. Inferior Myocardial Infarction. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2023 Feb 12. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29262146/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94805"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"39"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19498"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19498"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c9408a08-eda9-4681-a2a5-6787c9a41bbe.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c9408a08-eda9-4681-a2a5-6787c9a41bbe.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":603,"height":314}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94805"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-05T17:29:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-17T20:24:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"39"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112771"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id"